statement:
Let \emph{C} be the intersection of the plane

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}x+y+z=2\end{align*}

and the sphere

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}x^2+y^2+z^2=2.\end{align*}

Use Lagrange multipliers to find the maximum value of \emph{$f$(x,y,z)=z}
on \emph{C}.

hints:
Get the equations in this Lagrange multiplier problem by setting the
partial derivatives of the objective function, $\Lambda$, to zero, where

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \Lambda(x,y,z,\mu,\nu) = f(x,y,z) + \mu(x + y + z - 2) + \nu(x^{2} + y^{2} + z^{2} - 2)\end{align*}
